The parallelepiped formed by the vectors $AB$, $AC$ and $AP$ is given by
(the absolute value of) the determinant of the three vectors. From
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH152/April_2012/Question_1_(a)}{1(a)}
and
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH152/April_2012/Question_1_(c)}{1(c)},
we have that

\begin{align*}
\vec{AB}&=[-2,2,1]\\
\vec{AC}&=[-1,1,1]\end{align*}

and so all we need is $\vec{AP}$,

\begin{align*}\vec{AP}=P-A=[0,-1,0].\end{align*}

Therefore, the volume of the parallelepiped is given by

\begin{align*}
\textrm{volume}&=\left|\textrm{det}
\begin{pmatrix}
-2  &  2  &  1\\
-1  &  1  &  1\\
0  &  -1  &  0
\end{pmatrix}\right|\\
&=\left|-1\textrm{det}
\begin{pmatrix}
-2  &  1\\
-1  &  1
\end{pmatrix}\right|\\
&=|-2+1|=|-1|=1.\end{align*}
